I think there’s an interesting insight in that, but I’d phrase it a bit differently.

People-pleasing is often driven by avoiding disapproval. It adapts to whatever the other person wants, even at the expense of your own judgment.

Charisma isn’t the opposite of that. At its best, charisma comes from a combination of:

* conviction,
* presence,
* authenticity,
* and genuine interest in other people.

Someone charismatic doesn’t necessarily tell everyone what they want to hear. In fact, some of the most charismatic people are willing to say things others disagree with. What draws people is that their words, actions, and values appear aligned.

So I might frame it like this:

* People-pleasing asks, “How do I get them to like me?”
* Charisma asks, “How do I show up so clearly that people understand who I am and what I stand for?”

Those lead to very different behaviors.

For someone building a company like Wild Hawg, that distinction matters. A brand that tries to please everyone often becomes forgettable. A brand with a clear identity attracts the people it’s meant for and naturally turns away those it isn’t.

The caution I’d add is that charisma can be used in healthy or unhealthy ways. It can inspire, teach, and unite—but it can also manipulate if it’s used to bypass people’s judgment instead of earning their trust.

The kind of charisma that tends to last is built on credibility. People don’t just feel energized in the moment; over time they learn, “When this person says they’ll do something, they follow through.”

In that sense, charisma isn’t a replacement for integrity or execution. It amplifies them. Without them, it eventually fades.